WEBVTT

00:28.500 --> 00:29.980
CHAPTER IX.

00:30.920 --> 00:32.460
Powder and Arms.

00:36.620 --> 00:42.520
The Hispaniola lay some way out, and we went under the figureheads and round the

00:42.520 --> 00:49.400
stearns of many other ships, and their cables sometimes grated underneath our keel and

00:49.400 --> 00:58.020
sometimes swung above us. At last, however, we got alongside and were met and saluted as

00:58.020 --> 01:04.360
we stepped aboard by the mate, Mr. Arrow, a brown old sailor with earrings in his

01:04.360 --> 01:11.940
ears and a squint. He and the squire were very thick and friendly, but I soon

01:11.940 --> 01:16.520
observed that things were not the same between Mr. Trelawney and the captain.

01:19.000 --> 01:24.640
This last was a sharp-looking man who seemed angry with everything on board and

01:24.640 --> 01:31.460
soon to tell us why, for we had hardly got down into the cabin when a sailor followed us.

01:33.580 --> 01:38.100
Captain Smollett, sir, asking to speak with you, said he.

01:39.760 --> 01:44.640
I am always at the captain's orders. Show him in, said the squire.

01:49.020 --> 01:57.360
Well, Captain Smollett, what have you to say? All well, I hope? All ship-shape and seaworthy?

01:58.340 --> 02:05.760
Well, sir, said the captain. Better speak plain, I believe, even at the risk of offense.

02:07.020 --> 02:14.480
I don't like this cruise. I don't like the men, and I don't like my officer. That's

02:14.480 --> 02:23.660
sweet. Perhaps, sir, you don't like the ship, inquired the squire, very angry as I could see.

02:25.060 --> 02:32.200
I can't speak to that, sir, not having seen her tried, said the captain. She seems a clever

02:32.200 --> 02:42.200
craft. More I can't say. Possibly, sir, you may not like your employer either, says the squire.

02:43.100 --> 02:45.500
But here Dr. Livesey cut in.

02:47.300 --> 02:55.460
Stay a bit, said he. Stay a bit. No use of such questions as that but to produce ill feeling.

02:56.740 --> 03:03.000
The captain has said too much, or he has said too little, and I'm bound to say that I require

03:03.000 --> 03:11.220
an explanation of his words. You don't, you say, like this cruise. Now why?

03:13.360 --> 03:20.180
I was engaged, sir, on what we call sealed orders, to sail this ship for that gentleman

03:20.180 --> 03:28.540
where he should bid me, said the captain. So far so good. But now I find that every man before

03:28.540 --> 03:39.120
the mast knows more than I do. I don't call that fair now, do you? No, said Dr. Livesey. I don't.

03:41.000 --> 03:48.040
Next, said the captain. I learn we are going after treasure. Hear it from my own hands,

03:48.280 --> 03:55.720
mind you. Now treasure is ticklish work. I don't like treasure voyages on any account,

03:55.720 --> 04:02.240
and I don't like them above all when they are secret and when, begging your pardon,

04:02.420 --> 04:06.060
Mr. Trelawney, the secret has been told to the parrot.

04:08.680 --> 04:17.040
Silver's parrot? asked the squire. It's a way of speaking, said the captain. Blabbed, I mean.

04:18.020 --> 04:24.400
It's my belief neither of you gentlemen know what you are about, but I'll tell you my way of it.

04:24.400 --> 04:28.460
Life or death, and a close run.

04:30.200 --> 04:36.860
That is all clear, and I dare say true enough, replied Dr. Livesey.

04:37.400 --> 04:41.840
We take the risk, but we are not so ignorant as you believe us.

04:43.300 --> 04:48.280
Next, you say you don't like the crew. Are they not good seamen?

04:49.240 --> 04:56.640
I don't like them, sir, returned Captain Smollett, and I think I should have had the choosing of my

04:56.640 --> 05:06.540
own hands if you go to that. Perhaps you should, replied the doctor. My friend should perhaps have

05:06.540 --> 05:13.760
taken you along with him, but the slight, if there be one, was unintentional. And you don't

05:13.760 --> 05:17.260
like Mr. Arrow? I don't, sir.

05:17.880 --> 05:23.280
I believe he's a good seamen, but he's too free with the crew to be a good officer.

05:24.680 --> 05:30.360
A mate should keep himself to himself, shouldn't drink with the men before the mast.

05:32.040 --> 05:35.040
Do you mean he drinks? cried the squire.

05:36.340 --> 05:40.720
No, sir, replied the captain. Only that he's too familiar.

05:42.360 --> 05:51.040
Well, now, and the short and long of it, Captain? asked the doctor. Tell us what you want.

05:53.180 --> 05:57.360
Well, gentlemen, are you determined to go on this cruise?

05:59.000 --> 06:01.640
Like iron, answered the squire.

06:03.560 --> 06:05.640
Very good, said the captain.

06:06.600 --> 06:12.280
Then, as you've heard me very patiently, saying things that I could not prove,

06:13.260 --> 06:19.540
hear me a few words more. They are putting the powder and the arms in the forehold.

06:20.960 --> 06:25.120
Now you have a good place under the cabin. Why not put them there?

06:26.520 --> 06:27.480
First point.

06:29.740 --> 06:33.560
Then, you are bringing four of your own people with you,

06:33.780 --> 06:36.960
and they tell me some of them are to be birthed forward.

06:38.080 --> 06:41.220
Why not give them the births here beside the cabin?

06:42.740 --> 06:48.100
Second point. Any more? asked Mr. Turillani.

06:50.220 --> 06:55.840
One more, said the captain. There's been too much blabbing already.

06:57.480 --> 07:00.180
Far too much, agreed the doctor.

07:02.200 --> 07:10.380
I'll tell you what I've heard myself, continued Captain Smollett, that you have a map of an island,

07:11.820 --> 07:18.500
that there's crosses on the map to show where treasure is, and that the island lies.

07:20.240 --> 07:25.300
And then he named the latitude and longitude exactly.

07:27.480 --> 07:31.400
I never told that, cried the squire, to a soul.

07:32.900 --> 07:36.060
The hands know it, sir, returned the captain.

07:38.320 --> 07:42.580
Livesey, that must have been you or Hawkins, cried the squire.

07:44.540 --> 07:48.600
It doesn't much matter who it was, replied the doctor.

07:49.640 --> 07:56.140
And I could see that neither he nor the captain paid much regard to Mr. Turillani's protestations.

07:57.640 --> 08:02.010
Neither did I, to be sure. He was so loose a talker.

08:03.220 --> 08:10.120
Yet in this case I believe he was really right, and that nobody had told the situation of the island.

08:13.180 --> 08:19.720
Well, gentlemen, continued the captain, I don't know who has this map,

08:20.620 --> 08:26.280
but I make it a point. It shall be kept secret even from me and Mr. Arrow.

08:27.600 --> 08:30.360
Otherwise I would ask you to let me resign.

08:33.080 --> 08:35.280
I see, said the doctor.

08:37.080 --> 08:43.040
You wish us to keep this matter dark, and to make a garrison of the stern part of the ship,

08:43.980 --> 08:50.200
manned with my friend's own people, and provided with all the arms and powder on board.

08:51.700 --> 08:54.820
In other words, you fear a mutiny.

08:56.840 --> 09:07.100
Sir, said Captain Smollett, with no intention to take offence, I deny your right to put words into my mouth.

09:08.780 --> 09:16.280
No captain, sir, would be justified in going to sea at all if he had ground enough to say that.

09:18.440 --> 09:22.920
As for Mr. Arrow, I believe him thoroughly honest.

09:23.880 --> 09:28.680
Some of the men are the same. All may be for what I know.

09:30.860 --> 09:37.380
But I am responsible for the ship's safety, and the life of every man jack aboard of her.

09:39.020 --> 09:43.560
I see things going, as I think, not quite right.

09:44.880 --> 09:50.560
And I ask you to take certain precautions, or let me resign my berth.

09:52.180 --> 09:54.560
And that's all.

09:57.400 --> 10:00.860
Captain Smollett, began the doctor with a smile.

10:02.400 --> 10:05.980
Did ever you hear the fable of the mountain and the mouse?

10:07.900 --> 10:12.700
You'll excuse me, I dare say, but you remind me of that fable.

10:14.380 --> 10:19.640
When you came in here, I'll stake my wig. You meant more than this.

10:22.420 --> 10:25.820
Doctor, said the captain, you are smart.

10:27.160 --> 10:34.540
When I came in here, I meant to get discharged. I had no thought that Mr. Trelawney would hear a word.

10:36.620 --> 10:44.860
No more I would, cried the squire. Had Livesey not been here, I should have seen you to the deuce.

10:45.640 --> 10:54.480
As it is, I have heard you. I will do as you desire, but I think the worse of you.

10:56.700 --> 11:02.900
That's as you please, sir, said the captain. You'll find I do my duty.

11:05.300 --> 11:07.460
And with that he took his leave.

11:10.700 --> 11:20.400
Trelawney, said the doctor, contrary to all my notions, I believe you have managed to get two honest men on board with you.

11:21.600 --> 11:23.940
That man and John Silver.

11:26.220 --> 11:29.160
Silver if you like, cried the squire.

11:30.160 --> 11:40.290
But as for that intolerable humbug, I declare I think his conduct unmanly, unsalerly, and downright un-English.

11:42.800 --> 11:47.900
Well, says the doctor, we shall see.

11:50.920 --> 12:03.380
When we came on deck, the men had begun already to take out the arms and powder, yo-hoing at their work, while the captain and Mr. Arrow stood by superintending.

12:06.760 --> 12:09.340
The new arrangement was quite to my liking.

12:10.620 --> 12:18.840
The whole schooner had been overhauled, six berths had been made a stern out of what had been the after part of the main hold,

12:19.840 --> 12:27.200
and this set of cabins was only joined to the galley and forecastle by a sparred passage on the port side.

12:29.000 --> 12:40.210
It had been originally meant that the captain, Mr. Arrow, Hunter, Joyce, the doctor, and the squire were to occupy these six berths.

12:42.640 --> 12:50.160
Now Redruth and I were to get two of them, and Mr. Arrow and the captain were to sleep on deck in the companion,

12:50.920 --> 12:55.700
which had been enlarged on each side till you might have almost called it a roundhouse.

12:57.600 --> 13:07.200
Very low it was still, of course, but there was room to swing two hammocks, and even the mate seemed pleased with the arrangement.

13:10.100 --> 13:21.420
Even he, perhaps, had been doubtful as to the crew, but that is only guess, for as you shall hear, we had not long the benefit of his opinion.

13:24.860 --> 13:36.280
We were all hard at work, changing the powder and the berths, when the last man or two, and Long John along with them, came off in a shoreboat.

13:39.080 --> 13:45.020
The cook came up the side like a monkey for cleverness, and as soon as he saw what was doing,

13:45.740 --> 13:49.360
So ho, mates! says he. What's this?

13:51.080 --> 13:55.180
We're a changing of the powder, Jack, answers one.

13:56.400 --> 14:03.320
Why, by the powers! cried Long John. If we do, we'll miss the morning tide.

14:05.220 --> 14:13.360
My orders, said the captain shortly. You may go below, my man. Hands will want supper.

14:15.220 --> 14:23.780
Aye, aye, sir, answered the cook, and touching his forelock, he disappeared at once in the direction of his galley.

14:26.140 --> 14:29.120
That's a good man, captain, said the doctor.

14:31.020 --> 14:34.220
Very likely, sir, replied Captain Smollett.

14:35.580 --> 14:37.940
Easy with that, men, easy!

14:38.920 --> 14:49.400
He ran on to the fellows who were shifting the powder, and then suddenly observing me examining the swivel we carried amid ships, along Brass Nine.

14:50.480 --> 14:57.980
Hear you, ships boy! he cried. Out of that! Off with you to the cook, and get some work!

15:00.160 --> 15:09.360
And then, as I was hurrying off, I heard him say quite loudly to the doctor, I'll have no favourites on my ship.

15:11.360 --> 15:19.000
I assure you, I was quite of the squire's way of thinking, and hated the captain deeply.

15:20.540 --> 15:24.000
End of chapter 9

15:27.180 --> 15:31.240
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson

15:31.960 --> 15:36.000
Chapter 10 The Voyage

15:38.200 --> 15:52.460
All that night we were in a great bustle getting things stowed in their place, and boatfuls of the squire's friends, Mr. Blandly and the like, coming off to wish him a good voyage and a safe return.

15:54.560 --> 15:59.400
We never had a night at the Admiral Benbow when I had half the work.

16:00.860 --> 16:10.720
And I was dog-tired when, a little before dawn, the boatswain sounded his pipe, and the crew began to man the capstan bars.

16:12.820 --> 16:20.840
I might have been twice as weary, yet I would not have left the deck. All was so new and interesting to me.

16:20.840 --> 16:29.940
The brief commands, the shrill note of the whistle, the men bustling to their places in the glimmer of the ship's lanterns.

16:32.960 --> 16:38.100
Now, Barbecue, tip us a stave, cried one voice.

16:39.460 --> 16:41.580
The old one, cried another.

16:43.260 --> 16:53.820
Ay, ay, mates, said Long John, who was standing by with his crutch under his arm, and at once broke out in the air, and words I knew so well.

16:55.060 --> 16:58.020
Fifteen men on the dead man's chest.

16:59.200 --> 17:01.640
And the whole crew bore chorus.

17:02.860 --> 17:06.480
Yo ho ho, and a bottle a rum.

17:08.400 --> 17:12.900
And at the third ho, drove the bars before them with a will.

17:15.480 --> 17:25.600
Even at that exciting moment it carried me back to the old Admiral Benbow in a second, and I seemed to hear the voice of the captain piping in the chorus.

17:28.020 --> 17:34.200
But soon the anchor was short up. Soon it was hanging, dripping at the bows.

17:35.780 --> 17:42.100
Soon the sails began to draw, and the land and shipping to flit by on either side.

17:43.540 --> 17:51.060
And before I could lie down to snatch an hour of slumber, the Hispaniola had begun her voyage to the Isle of Treasure.

17:54.100 --> 17:58.440
I am not going to relate that voyage in detail.

17:59.660 --> 18:01.420
It was fairly prosperous.

18:03.020 --> 18:11.780
The ship proved to be a good ship, the crew were capable seamen, and the captain thoroughly understood his business.

18:13.480 --> 18:20.640
But before we came the length of Treasure Island, two or three things had happened which required to be known.

18:23.620 --> 18:29.260
Mr. Arrow, first of all, turned out even worse than the captain had feared.

18:31.180 --> 18:36.140
He had no command among the men, and people did what they pleased with him.

18:37.640 --> 18:49.540
But that was by no means the worst of it, for after a day or two at sea he began to appear on deck with hazy eye, red cheeks, stuttering tongue,

18:50.260 --> 18:52.540
and other marks of drunkenness.

18:54.880 --> 18:57.840
Time after time he was ordered below in disgrace.

19:00.400 --> 19:07.780
Sometimes he fell and cut himself, sometimes he lay all day long in his little bunk at one side of the companion,

19:09.600 --> 19:16.780
sometimes for a day or two he would be almost sober and attend to his work at least passably.

19:20.280 --> 19:24.340
In the meantime we could never make out where he got the drink.

19:25.720 --> 19:27.480
That was the ship's mystery.

19:28.980 --> 19:32.780
Watch him as we pleased, we could do nothing to solve it.

19:33.480 --> 19:38.740
And when we asked him to his face, he would only laugh if he were drunk,

19:39.420 --> 19:45.060
and if he were sober deny solemnly that he ever tasted anything but water.

19:47.640 --> 19:53.440
He was not only useless as an officer and a bad influence amongst the men,

19:54.140 --> 19:58.660
but it was plain that at this rate he must soon kill himself outright.

20:01.000 --> 20:14.160
So nobody was much surprised, nor very sorry, when one dark night with a head sea he disappeared entirely and was seen no more.

20:17.380 --> 20:19.640
Overboard, said the captain.

20:21.160 --> 20:25.440
Well, gentlemen, that saves the trouble of putting him in irons.

20:28.300 --> 20:35.080
But there we were, without a mate, and it was necessary, of course, to advance one of the men.

20:36.860 --> 20:41.620
The bosom, Job Anderson, was the likeliest man aboard,

20:42.340 --> 20:45.940
and though he kept his old title he served in a way as mate.

20:48.380 --> 20:53.240
Mr. Trelawney had followed the sea, and his knowledge made him very useful,

20:54.020 --> 20:57.000
for he often took a watch himself in easy weather.

20:58.200 --> 21:06.160
And the coxswain, Israel Hands, was a careful, wily, old, experienced seaman,

21:06.580 --> 21:09.440
who could be trusted at a pinch with almost anything.

21:13.020 --> 21:15.800
He was a great confidant of Long John Silver,

21:16.540 --> 21:21.180
and so the mention of his name leads me to speak of our ship's cook,

21:21.900 --> 21:24.220
Barbecue, as the men called him.

21:28.060 --> 21:31.820
Aboard ship he carried his crutch by a lanyard round his neck,

21:32.580 --> 21:35.060
to have both hands as free as possible.

21:36.560 --> 21:40.620
It was something to see him wedge the foot of the crutch against a bulkhead,

21:41.480 --> 21:45.140
and propped against it, yielding to every movement of the ship,

21:46.120 --> 21:49.020
still get on with his cooking like someone safe ashore.

21:51.200 --> 21:55.560
Still more strange was it to see him in the heaviest of weather cross the deck.

21:57.700 --> 22:02.320
He had a line or two rigged up to help him across the widest spaces,

22:03.360 --> 22:05.160
Long John's earrings they were called,

22:05.680 --> 22:08.540
and he would hand himself from one place to another,

22:09.280 --> 22:13.760
now using the crutch, now trailing it alongside by the lanyard,

22:14.220 --> 22:16.360
as quickly as another man could walk.

22:18.900 --> 22:24.140
Yet some of the men who had sailed with him before expressed their pity to see him so reduced.

22:27.340 --> 22:31.600
He's no common man, Barbecue, said the coxswain to me.

22:32.720 --> 22:35.000
He had good schooling in his young days,

22:35.460 --> 22:37.820
and can speak like a book when so minded,

22:38.460 --> 22:42.760
and brave, a lion's nothing alongside of Long John.

22:43.940 --> 22:48.320
I seen him grapple for and knock their heads together, him unarmed.

22:50.900 --> 22:54.640
All the crew respected, and even obeyed him.

22:55.840 --> 23:01.480
He had a way of talking to each, and doing everybody some particular service.

23:03.520 --> 23:05.800
To me he was unwiridly kind,

23:06.460 --> 23:10.900
and always glad to see me in the galley, which he kept as clean as a new pin,

23:12.060 --> 23:16.000
the dishes hanging up burnished, and his parrot in a cage in one corner.

23:17.960 --> 23:23.360
Come away, Hawkins, he would say, come and have a yarn with John.

23:24.350 --> 23:27.140
Nobody more welcome than yourself, my son.

23:28.580 --> 23:30.320
Sit you down and hear the news.

23:31.580 --> 23:32.820
Here's Captain Flint.

23:33.960 --> 23:37.430
I calls my parrot Captain Flint after the famous buccaneer.

23:38.780 --> 23:42.260
Here's Captain Flint predicting success to our voyage.

23:42.920 --> 23:43.900
Wasn't you, Captain?

23:45.420 --> 23:48.500
And the parrot would say with great rapidity,

23:48.500 --> 23:52.500
Pieces of eight, pieces of eight, pieces of eight,

23:52.840 --> 23:55.380
till you wondered that it was not out of breath,

23:56.240 --> 23:59.060
or till John threw his handkerchief over the cage.

24:02.100 --> 24:08.500
Now that bird, he would say, is maybe two hundred years old, Hawkins.

24:09.500 --> 24:15.940
They live forever mostly, and if anybody's seen more wickedness it must be the devil himself.

24:17.660 --> 24:21.840
She's sailed with England, the great Captain England, the pirate.

24:23.200 --> 24:31.340
She's been at Madagascar, and Malabar, and Suriname, and Providence, and Portobello.

24:33.260 --> 24:36.280
She was at the fishing up of the wrecked plate ships.

24:37.760 --> 24:41.280
It's there she learned pieces of eight, and little wonder,

24:42.160 --> 24:45.040
three hundred and fifty thousand of them Hawkins.

24:46.360 --> 24:50.700
She was at the boarding of the Viceroy of the Indies out of Goa she was,

24:50.800 --> 24:54.360
and to look at her you would think she was a baby.

24:56.120 --> 24:59.420
But you smelt powder, didn't you, Captain?

25:01.440 --> 25:04.660
Stand by to go about, the parrot would scream.

25:06.840 --> 25:10.640
Ah, she's a handsome craft she is, the cook would say,

25:11.680 --> 25:13.340
and give her sugar from his pocket.

25:13.340 --> 25:20.640
And then the bird would peck at the bars and swear straight on passing belief for wickedness.

25:22.500 --> 25:28.320
There, John would add, you can't touch pitch and not be mucked lad.

25:29.820 --> 25:34.260
Here's this poor old innocent bird of mine swearing blue fire,

25:35.000 --> 25:37.340
and none the wiser you may lay to that.

25:38.360 --> 25:41.800
She would swear the same in a manner of speaking before Chaplain.

25:43.840 --> 25:50.320
And John would touch his forelock with a solemn way he had that made me think he was the best of men.

25:53.500 --> 25:59.540
In the meantime, the squire and Captain Smollett were still on pretty distant terms with one another.

26:01.380 --> 26:03.700
The squire made no bones about the matter.

26:04.460 --> 26:06.020
He despised the captain.

26:08.400 --> 26:12.600
The captain on his part never spoke but when he was spoken to,

26:12.600 --> 26:17.400
and then sharp and short and dry, and not a word wasted.

26:19.520 --> 26:25.500
He owned, when driven into a corner, that he seemed to have been wrong about the crew,

26:26.780 --> 26:31.940
that some of them were as brisk as he wanted to see and all had behaved fairly well.

26:34.800 --> 26:38.940
As for the ship, he had taken a downright fancy to her.

26:39.860 --> 26:45.940
Shall I appoint nearer the wind than a man has a right to expect of his own married wife, sir?

26:47.460 --> 26:53.800
But, he would add, all I say is, we're not home again.

26:54.720 --> 26:56.940
And I don't like the crews.

26:59.000 --> 27:04.520
The squire had this, would turn away and march up and down the deck chin in air.

27:06.220 --> 27:11.500
A trifle more of that man, he would say, and I shall explode.

27:16.240 --> 27:21.740
We had some heavy weather, which only proved the qualities of the Hispaniola.

27:23.320 --> 27:29.880
Every man on board seemed well content, and they must have been hard to please if they had been otherwise.

27:29.880 --> 27:37.260
For it is my belief there never was a ship's company so spoiled since Noah put to sea.

27:39.460 --> 27:41.720
Double grog was going on the least excuse.

27:42.760 --> 27:48.360
There was duff on odd days as, for instance, if the squire heard it was any man's birthday.

27:49.860 --> 27:56.120
And always a barrel of apples standing broached in the waste for anyone to help himself that had a fancy.

27:58.880 --> 28:04.020
Never knew good come of it yet, the captain said to Dr. Livesey.

28:04.080 --> 28:08.440
Spoil folks for hands, make devils, that's my belief.

28:10.840 --> 28:15.000
But good did come of the apple barrel, as you shall hear.

28:16.360 --> 28:25.360
For if it had not been for that, we should have had no note of warning, and might all have perished by the hand of treachery.

28:27.920 --> 28:30.600
This was how it came about.

28:33.300 --> 28:37.000
We had run up the trades to get the wind of the island we were after.

28:38.160 --> 28:40.040
I am not allowed to be more plain.

28:41.200 --> 28:45.460
And now we were running down for it with a bright lookout day and night.

28:47.760 --> 28:53.120
It was about the last day of our outward voyage by the largest computation.

28:54.820 --> 29:02.280
Sometime that night, or at latest before noon of the morrow, we should sight the treasure island.

29:04.760 --> 29:11.000
We were heading south-southwest and had a steady breeze abeam and a quiet sea.

29:13.220 --> 29:19.120
The Hispaniola rolled steadily, dipping her bow-spirit now and then with a whiff of spray.

29:20.920 --> 29:23.380
All was drawing low and aloft.

29:24.580 --> 29:30.660
Everyone was in the bravest spirits, because we were now so near an end of the first part of our adventure.

29:34.100 --> 29:43.180
Now after sundown, when all my work was over and I was on my way to my birth, it occurred to me that I should like an apple.

29:45.080 --> 29:46.560
I ran on deck.

29:47.500 --> 29:50.660
The watch was all forward looking out for the island.

29:52.220 --> 29:57.340
The man at the helm was watching the luff of the sail and whistling away gently to himself.

29:58.880 --> 30:06.460
And that was the only sound excepting the swish of the sea against the bows and around the sides of the ship.

30:09.420 --> 30:15.060
In I got bodily to the apple-barrel and found there was scarce an apple left.

30:15.820 --> 30:22.600
But sitting down there in the dark, what with the sound of the waters and the rocking movement of the ship,

30:23.920 --> 30:32.400
I had either fallen asleep or was on the point of doing so when a heavy man sat down with rather a clash close by.

30:35.160 --> 30:43.600
The barrel shook as he leaned his shoulders against it, and I was just about to jump up when the man began to speak.

30:45.640 --> 30:48.140
It was Silver's voice.

30:49.780 --> 30:56.680
And before I had heard a dozen words, I would not have shown myself for all the world,

30:57.740 --> 31:04.200
but lay there, trembling and listening in the extreme of fear and curiosity.

31:05.660 --> 31:17.460
For from these dozen words I understood that the lives of all the honest men aboard depended upon me alone.

